	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Brian,<BR>
There is one MAJOR flaw to your idea.<BR>
You are level 14.<BR>
You are killing blues all day long and getting 100 exp (to use your example) knowing that the penalty of dying is 1000.<BR>
Then a Hill Giant wanders by and kills you.  You would have gotten 1000 exp for killing it, but it just took away 10000 exp because you couldn't get out of the way in time.<BR>
<BR>
The obvious argument to this is to make the EASY stuff take away more experience.  However, consider this example.<BR>
You are level 30.<BR>
You are killing blues all day long and getting 1000 exp knowing that the penalty of dying is 10000.<BR>
Then a green orc wanders by and kills you while you are resting after a close battle.  You would have gotten 1 exp for killing it, but it just took away 100000 exp because you were so wounded from a previous battle.<BR>
<BR>
Therefore, in my opinion, the best thing to do is to keep it the way it is, with a percentage of your current exp gained.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
